{"blocks":[{"key":"7bivn","text":"Pick a colony from each strain's plate and resuspend it in the media.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"7c71m","text":"Instructor Tips","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":15}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fkm9l","text":"This assumes that, once you or your students have identified yeast colonies with successful knockouts, you have struck them out on plates","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9sds9","text":"Log-phase growth is the most reproducible growth mode for yeast. This is why the experiment should start in log phase and why doubling time should be computed in log phase.","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"obv7","text":"Growing the cells in double-strength media means that they can be diluted 1:1 and still be in \"complete\" media for the stress experiment.","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6ub47","text":"Yeast cells are heavy and settle rapidly toward the bottom of a test-tube. Make sure you vortex them before measuring OD600; vortex again before subculturing; and vortex again before putting them in an assay plate.","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dpc3d","text":"Computing doubling time is not optional! Because we're looking at an exponential phenomenon, a small difference in starting concentration is rapidly amplified and can \"look\" on a graph like a strain is growing slower.","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bitu9","text":"I thought everyone graduated highschool with a basic ability to use a spreadsheet?
